'''Anton Atanas Sielava''' ({{lang-be|Антон Сялява}}, {{lang-uk|Антін Селява}}, {{lang-pl|Antoni Sielawa}}) (1583 &ndash; 5 October 1655) was the [[List of Major Archbishops of Kiev–Galicia|Metropolitan of Kiev, Galicia and Russia]] of the [[Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church]] from 1641 to his death in 1655.

==Life==
Atanas Sielava was born on about 1583 in the [[Polotsk Voivodeship]] from a family of Cossack origin and belonging to the Orthodox religion. In 1612 he entered in the [[Order of Saint Basil the Great]], in the monastery of the Holy Trinity in [[Vilnius]],{{r|EP}} taking the religious name of Anton (Antony). He lived for some time in the same cell with [[Josaphat Kuntsevych|Saint Josaphat Kuntsevich]] and he was ordained a [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priest]] in 1617. He studied in the [[Roman Colleges#Collegio Greco|Greek College in Rome]] from 1617 to September 1619.{{r|PGCR}}

On 12 November 1623 the bishop of [[Polotsk]], Josaphat Kuntsevich (later declared a [[Saint]]), was killed by an Orthodox mob. After him, Anton Sielava was appointed to the [[episcopal see|See]] of Polotsk.{{r|EOU}} He was consecrated a [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|bishop]] in early 1624 by Metropolitan [[Joseph Rutski]] and enthroned on 14 February 1624.{{r|HKV}}

To Metropolitan Joseph Rutski succeeded Metropolitan [[Rafajil Korsak]], who, when in 1639 left [[Belarus]] to go to [[Rome]] for [[Visit ad Limina]], appointed Sielava as [[Vicarius]] for the Church. Rafajil Korsak died in Rome in August 1640 and, according to his last will, [[Pope Urban VIII]] confirmed Sielava as new Metropolitan after the usual process of eligibility.{{r|EP}} Anton Sielava was so formally appointed Metropolitan of Kiev on 18 March 1641.{{r|HC4}} His patriarchate was initially marked by the [[beatification]], on 16 May 1643, of Josaphat Kuntsevich.

Following his predecessors Joseph Rutski and Rafajil Korsak, Sielava went on in negotiations with the Orthodox Patriarch of Kiev, [[Peter Mogila]] about the way to unify the Ukrainian Church.{{r|Baran}} However he was not a person of the stamp of his predecessors, and after the death of Mogila (1646), the discussions ended without results.

Sielava left much part of the administration of the Church to others, and he was of a sickly disposition and quite [[hypochondriac]],{{r|Senyk}} and in the last part of his life he was seriously ill and blind.{{r|Pelesz}}

Since 1648, the political situation in the [[Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth]] underwent years of crisis due to the [[Khmelnytsky Uprising]], a [[Cossack]] rebellion in [[Ukraine]] fiercely anti-Catholic, followed by the [[Russo-Polish War (1654-1667)]] and [[Second Northern War]]. The Greek-Catholic Church was seriously threaten, many churches, monasteries and schools were destroyed, and priests and monks killed.{{r|Baran|page1=231}} Sielava had to leave Polotsk and died on 5 October 1655,{{r|HKV}} when already (since 1653) the Greek-Catholic Church was in the resolute hands of [[Gabriel Kolenda]].

==Works==
Anton Sielava was also a writer and a [[polemist]]. Among his works we have his "''Antelenchus''", against the "''Elenchum''" of [[Meletius Smotrytski]], and his "''Vitam Servi Dei  Josaphat, Archiepiscopi Polocensis''" (Life of the Servant of God Josaphat, bishop of Polotsk) edited in 1624.{{r|EP}}

