{{Infobox person |name = Renata Litvinova |image = Рената.jpg |birth_name = Renata Muratovna Litvinova |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|1|12|df=yes}} |birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]] |occupation = [[Film actress]], [[Film director|director]], [[screenwriter]] |website = http://renatalitvinova.ru/ |notable_works = |children = 1 daughter, Ulyana Dobrovskaya }}
'''Renata Muratovna Litvinova''' ({{lang-ru|Рената Муратовна Литвинова}}; born 12 January 1967) is a [[Russia]]n actress, director, and screenwriter.<ref>{{cite web|title=LITVINOVA Renata (Actress)|url=http://persona.rin.ru/eng/view/f/0/19020/LITVINOVA-Renata|website=Celebrities|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>
== Biography == Litvinova was born in Moscow to [[Volga Tatars|Volga Tatar]] father Murat Aminovich Vergazov and an [[Russians|ethnic Russian]] mother, Alisa Mikhailovna Litvinova.<ref name="rusact">{{cite web|title=Renata Litvinova|url=http://www.rusactors.ru/l/litvinova/index.shtml|website=Rusactors|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> Her parents were doctors by profession. They divorced when Renata was just one year old. She attended [[VGIK]] in 1984 and graduated in 1989.<ref name="Cosmopolitan">{{cite web|title=Biography of the Stars - Renata Litvinova|url=http://www.cosmo.ru/stars/biography/renata-litvinova/#|website=Cosmopolitan|publisher=Cosmopolitan|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> She attended the same year as fellow screenwriters and directors Roman Kachanov and Arkady Vysotsky.<ref name="rusact"/> It is here where she worked on her first film as a screenwriter for the film ''The Much Loved rita. The Last Meeting with Her'' (1988).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kolobrotov|first1=Aleksei|title=Renata and Death|url=http://svpressa.ru/culture/article/63600/|website=The Free Press|publisher=The Free Press|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>
== Career ==
=== Screenwriter === She began her film career as a screenwriter, writing films from 1988 to 1998. None of her earlier projects such as ''Truck Drivers 2'' (1992) achieved any critical or commercial acclaim.<ref name="rusact"/> She was discovered by fellow director Kira Muratova in 1994 after Muratova had come across Litvinova's thesis she had written for VGIK. Meeting one another at a local festival, Muratova changed her mind and instead wanted Litvinova to star in one of her films.<ref name="rusact"/> Litvinova auditioned for the role of the female protagonist Violet but was deemed unsuitable. However, Muratova wanted her in the film and allowed her to write a role for herself. Litvinova wrote herself into the film as a nurse.<ref name="rusact"/> She continued to write screenplays after her role, which included both ''Male Revelations'' (1995) and ''Principled and Compassionate View'' (1995). The latter film won the Jury prize at the "Window to Europe" Film festival and was showcased in a number of other festivals around the world such as Japan and Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tokyo International Film Festival|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000655/1996|website=Internet Movie Database|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> She collaborated with Muratova again in 1997 and 1998, writing two screenplays that Muratova directed. Letanova's screenplay ''Three Stories'' was turned into a film in 1997, she also played the role of Opha in it. Her story ''To Own and Belong'' was adapted into the critically acclaimed crime film ''Country of the Deaf'' in 1998.<ref name="rusact"/> In 2017 Renata made her full debut in theatre with her own piece called "The North Wind" in Moscow Art Theatre. She was the director and screenwriter, as well as she played the key role in "The North Wind".
=== Actress ===
In 2000, she gained popularity after transitioning from a screenwriter to an actress, playing the role of Albino Crow in the show ''The Border''<ref name="Cosmopolitan"/> She wrote screenplays for films sparingly after this role and starred in all of the films she wrote. Litvinova became acclaimed in the mid-2000s when she was nominated for her roles in ''Sky. Plane. Girl.'' (2002), ''The Tuner'' (2004) and ''I’m Not Hurt'' (2006).<ref>{{cite web|title=Renata Litvinova - Awards|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0514852/awards?ref_=nm_ql_2|website=Internet Movie Database|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>
=== Director === She made her directorial debut in 2000 with the documentary ''There is No Death For Me''. The film focused on the experiences of Litvinova's favorite Soviet Era actresses and gave insight into her views on their stories.<ref>{{cite web|title=There Is No Death For Me|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/culture/2008/07/07/a_2776017.shtml|website=Newspaper.ru|publisher=Newspaper.ru|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> As with her screenwriting, she directed sparingly in between her acting roles, directing six films since 2000. She directed her first feature film in 2004, ''[[Goddess: How I fell in Love|The Goddess]]'', which she also wrote and starred in.<ref name="spsbio">{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://renatalitvinova.ru/%d0%b1%d0%b8%d0%be%d0%b3%d1%80%d0%b0%d1%84%d0%b8%d1%8f/|website=Renata Litvinova|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> In 2006, she directed her first short film, ''Rado''.<ref name="spsbio"/> Litvinova made her first foray into concert films in 2008 when she directed the film ''Green Theatre in Zemfira''. The film was created using footage from a concert of one of Litvinova's friends, musical artist Zemfira Ramazanova.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lapteva |first1=Elena |title=Zemfira without bills |url=http://www.kp.ru/daily/24038/97405/ |website=WebCite |accessdate=6 April 2015 |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/679kuuVNc |archivedate=April 24, 2012 }}</ref> The film won "music film of the year" from independent music award show "Steppenwolf".<ref>{{cite web|title=Green Theatre in Zemfira named best musical film|url=http://korrespondent.net/showbiz/cinema/495432-zelenyj-teatr-v-zemfire-nazvan-luchshim-muzykalnym-filmom|website=Correspondant.net|publisher=Correspondent|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> The two collaborated again in 2010 to create another Ramazanova concert film directed by Litvinova called ''Moscow. Crokus/Arrow''.<ref name="spsbio"/> Finally, Ramazanova served as the composer on Litvinova's second full-length feature film ''Rita's Last FairyTale'' (2012), which deals with "universal themes of love, hate and search for love."<ref>{{cite web|title=Rita's Last Fairytale|url=http://oiff.com.ua/en/films-2012/1801.htm|website=Odessa International Film Festival|publisher=Odessa International Film Festival|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Creators|url=http://ritaslastfairytale.ru/authors.html|website=Rita's Last Fairytale|publisher=Renata Litvinova|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>
===Voice Actress=== She lent her voice to the film ''$8.50'' (1999) to be used as a voiceover for the character Xenia who was played by Natalia Adreichenko. Her voice appeared in a number of other films in the 2000s including ''Frog's Paradise'' (2007) and ''Peregrine'' (2008).<ref name="spsbio"/>
