{{Infobox officeholder | name = '''Walter Audisio''' | image = Walter Audisio.jpg | nickname = Comandante Valerio | birth_date = {{birth date|1909|06|28}} | birth_place = [[Alessandria]], Italy | death_date = {{Death date and age|1973|10|11|1909|06|28}} | death_place = [[Rome]], Italy | restingplace = Cimitero Monumentale del Verano | occupation = [[Politician]], [[Revolutionary]] | nationality = Italian | party = [[Italian Communist Party]] | rank = Lieutenant Colonel, Inspector | unit = [[File:Flag of Italian Committee of National Liberation.svg|25px|border]] [[National Liberation Committee]] | office = [[Italian Chamber of Deputies]] | constituency = [[Alessandria]] | term_start = 1948 | term_end = 1963 | office2 = [[Italian Senate]] | term_start2 = 1963 | term_end2 = 1968 }} '''Walter Audisio''' (June 28, 1909 – October 11, 1973) was an [[Italian resistance movement|Italian partisan]] and communist politician. He was imprisoned before World War II for his anti-fascist activities. As a senior partisan he was involved in the [[death of Benito Mussolini]], possibly being the individual who killed the dictator and his mistress. After the war he served as an Italian deputy and later as a senator.
==Biography== ===Early activities=== In school, Audisio rose to the top of his class, and first worked making [[Borsalino]] hats. Next he worked for years as an [[Accountancy|accountant]] before entering a group of clandestine [[Anti-fascism|anti-fascists]] in 1931.<ref name=time/> The local group was discovered by the Italian [[secret police]], the Organization for Vigilance and Repression of Anti-Fascism (''Organizzazione per la Vigilanza e la Repressione dell'Antifascismo'', or [[OVRA]]) and in 1934, Audisio was sentenced to five years confinement on the island of [[Ponza]]. Released during [[World War II]], he resumed his activities against the government of [[Benito Mussolini]], and in September 1943 he started to organize the first bands of partisans in [[Casale Monferrato]]. During this time he held jobs in the Fascist civil service.<ref name=time/>
===Killing of Mussolini=== During the war, he joined the [[Italian Communist Party]] and became the inspector of the Garibaldi Brigades, a faction of the [[National Liberation Committee]] (CNL), commanding the formations operating in the [[Province of Mantova]] and the [[Po Valley]]. By January 1945, he had become the principal figure of the [[Italian resistance movement]] in [[Milan]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web |url= http://www.biography.com/search/article.do?id=9192204 |title= Walter Audisio Biography |work= [[Biography.com]] |year= 2007 |accessdate= 2008-04-08}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He used the ''[[Nom de guerre]]'' "Comandante Valerio", a name possibly also used by [[Luigi Longo]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/feb/28/guardianobituaries.italy |title= Urbano Lazzaro, The partisan who arrested Mussolini |first= John |last= Hooper |work= [[The Guardian]] |date= February 28, 2006 |accessdate= 2008-04-08}}</ref> As an official of the National Liberation Committee, he received an order on April 28, 1945 to enter [[Dongo, Italy|Dongo]] and enforce the [[capital punishment]] that had been decreed against Mussolini and others in the [[Fascism|fascist]] hierarchy.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/5314574.stm |title= Mussolini heir calls for inquest |work= [[BBC News]] |date= September 5, 2006 |accessdate= 2008-04-08}}</ref> The death of Mussolini remains shrouded in mystery today, but Audisio always claimed that he was the one who shot and killed the dictator and his mistress, [[Claretta Petacci]].<ref name=time>{{cite news |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,804084,00.html |title= What Price Brutus? |work= [[Time Magazine]] |date= April 7, 1947 |accessdate= 2008-04-08}}</ref>
===Post-war career=== After the war Audisio continued working with the communist movement, and in 1948, was elected to the [[Italian Chamber of Deputies]] for [[Alessandria]] with the [[Italian Communist Party]] as part of the [[Popular Democratic Front (Italy)|Popular Democratic Front]]. He supported the party until 1963, when he entered the [[Italian Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,820490,00.html?iid=chix-sphere |title= Battle on the Floor |work= [[Time Magazine]] |date= December 15, 1952 |accessdate= 2008-04-08}}</ref> In 1968 he left to work for Italian [[gasoline]] company [[Eni]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anpi.it/uomini/audisio_walter.htm |title=Walter Audisio |work=ANPI |date=January 9, 2006 |accessdate=2008-04-08 |language=Italian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605201455/http://www.anpi.it/uomini/audisio_walter.htm |archivedate=2008-06-05 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> He died five years later in 1973 of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.vipatients.com/patient_info.php?patient_id=3158 |work= VIPatients |title= Audisio, Walter |year= 2008 |publisher= GIDEON Informatics, Inc |accessdate= 2008-04-08}}</ref> His memoirs, titled ''In nome del popolo italiano'', were published two years after his death, in 1975.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/history_and_memory/v018/18.1ventresca.html |title= Mussolini's Ghost: Italy's Duce in History and Memory |first= Robert A. |last= Ventresca |publisher= Indiana University Press |journal= History & Memory |volume=18 |issue= 1 |year= 2006 |pages= 86–119 |accessdate= 2008-04-08 |doi= 10.1353/ham.2006.0008}}</ref>
